Generating Time Series of MA(1) with $\theta$ = 0.9, -0.9 and 0.3¶

In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
# import the module for simulating data
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_process import ArmaProcess

theta = [0.9, -0.9, 0.3]
panel = ['A', 'B', 'C']
fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(theta),3, figsize=(10,7))

for i in range(len(theta)):
    
    ax[i,0].set_ylim([-5,5]) 
    ax[i,0].set_ylabel('Panel ' + panel[i])
    ax[i,0].set_xlabel('t')
    ar = np.array([1])
    ma = np.array([1, -theta[i]])
    MA_object = ArmaProcess(ar, ma)  # creating object to generate time series data
    simulated_data = MA_object.generate_sample(nsample=500) # generate time series with n=500
    ax[i,0].plot(simulated_data)


    simulated_data_shift = np.append([float("nan")],simulated_data[0:-1])
    ax[i,1].set_ylabel('$Y_t$')
    ax[i,1].set_xlabel('$Y_{t-1}$')
    ax[i,1].scatter(simulated_data_shift,
                simulated_data, 
                color='orange',
                alpha=0.3) 

    simulated_data_shift2 = np.append([float("nan"),float("nan")],simulated_data[0:-2])
    ax[i,2].set_ylabel('$Y_t$')
    ax[i,2].set_xlabel('$Y_{t-2}$')
    ax[i,2].scatter(simulated_data_shift2,
                simulated_data, 
                color='green',
                alpha=0.3) 

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Examples of MA(2) with $\theta_1$ = 1 and $\theta_2$ = -0.6¶

In [3]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
# import the module for simulating data
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_process import ArmaProcess


theta1 = 1
theta2 = -0.6
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,4, figsize=(12,3))

ax[0].set_ylim([-5,5])
ax[0].set_ylabel('MA(2)')
ax[0].set_xlabel('t')
ar = np.array([1])
ma = np.array([1, -theta1, -theta2])
MA_object = ArmaProcess(ar, ma)
simulated_data = MA_object.generate_sample(nsample=1000)
ax[0].plot(simulated_data)


simulated_data_shift = np.append([ float("nan")],simulated_data[0:-1])
ax[1].set_ylabel('$Y_t$')
ax[1].set_xlabel('$Y_{t-1}$')
ax[1].scatter(simulated_data_shift,
            simulated_data, 
            color='orange',
            alpha=0.3) 

simulated_data_shift2 = np.append([ float("nan"),float("nan")],simulated_data[0:-2])
ax[2].set_ylabel('$Y_t$')
ax[2].set_xlabel('$Y_{t-2}$')
ax[2].scatter(simulated_data_shift2,
            simulated_data, 
            color='green',
            alpha=0.3) 

simulated_data_shift3 = np.append([ float("nan"),float("nan"),float("nan")],simulated_data[0:-3])
ax[3].set_ylabel('$Y_t$')
ax[3].set_xlabel('$Y_{t-3}$')
ax[3].scatter(simulated_data_shift3,
            simulated_data, 
            color='red',
            alpha=0.3) 

fig.tight_layout()

plt.show()

Autocorrelation Function for Several AR(1) Model¶

In [4]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
# import the module for simulating data
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_process import ArmaProcess
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf

phi = [0.9, 0.4, -0.8, -0.5]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, len(phi), figsize=(10,2))

for i in range(len(phi)):
    ar = np.array([1,-phi[i]])
    ma = np.array([1])
    AR_object = ArmaProcess(ar, ma)
    simulated_data = AR_object.generate_sample(nsample=100)
    ax[i].plot(simulated_data, color='red')
    ax[i].set_title('Model '+str(i+1))
    ax[i].set_ylim([-6,6])
   
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
# import the module for simulating data
from statsmodels.tsa.arima_process import ArmaProcess
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf

phi = [0.9, 0.4, -0.8, -0.5]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, len(phi), figsize=(10,2))

for i in range(len(phi)):
    ar = np.array([1,-phi[i]])
    ma = np.array([1])
    AR_object = ArmaProcess(ar, ma)
    simulated_data = AR_object.generate_sample(nsample=10000)
    plot_acf(simulated_data, lags=12, alpha=1, ax=ax[i])
    ax[i].set_title('Model '+str(i+1))
    ax[i].set_ylim([-1.2,1.2])
   
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
